[23-February-2026]
- I have modified the .ipynb workflow cell focused cell related to the CHEMBL data. The goal was to collect all CHEMBL bioactivity data for each target filtered to less than 100 micromolar. Then the model defines a potent binding event at 10 micromolar. So the compounds with bioactivity greater than 10 micromolar can be used as additional nonbinding compounds. However during the CHEMBL data pull make sure you collect nonbinders as well as low potent binders (nonbinders for our purpose).
- In the predict new compounds cell, there is an error with compound standardization, I think an early piece of the workflow was incomplete, causing issues in the later cell.
- MAJOR ISSUE: In the confusion matrix, there is still significant missed predictions of nonbinders as binders, likely due to the imbalance. Rethink ways to gather more nonbinding information from CHEMBL.
  - Are there compounds that have lots of difference bioactivity data (from multiple targets) within CHEMBL? Reports of large compound libraries across typical promiscuity assays such as CEREP panels?
  - Double check the SMOTE analysis portion of the workflow to make sure it is working to correct for the class imbalance.
- Make sure parts of the workflow are not erased, I want to keep functionality but make modifications where necessary.
- generate_report.py continues to run into errors when run in the pycharm environment. After running the workflow using run_pipeline.py, make sure generate_report.py runs as well.
  - Revise generate_report.py to serve as an interpreter of the output files from the workflow, the last cell that builds a analysis_report.md, and the standalone_predictions.csv generated on the withdrawn example compounds in the data directory.
      
[22-February-2026]
- The model selection portion of the script needs to be more holistic in the selection:
  - Model selection discrepancy. The RF was selected on ROC-AUC, but the MCDA composite ranking placed LightGBM first (0.948 vs 0.646). LightGBM's MCC (0.565 vs 0.393) is substantially better — critical given the 84:16 class imbalance. The RF's internal test MCC of 0.287 with 608 false positives vs 107 true negatives confirms poor minority-class discrimination.
  - Make sure that the final output includes the best holistic model prediction as well as a consensus accross the top three unique ML type models. This change needs to occur in the hold out set analysis and the novel compound analysis cells.
- The novel compound prediction section needs to handle out of domain compounds better.
  - What if a majority of compounds fall outside the applicability domain (kNN distance > 100), how should these predictions be handled.
  - Also make sure to standardize the "smiles" column in the novel compounds csv using RDKIT.
  - Rather than force a target value and column in the novel compound spreadsheet, all smiles will be run against all targets.
- Many of the NHRs have severe class imbalance (most have >75% binders), make sure to include some form of SMOTE analysis or correction to handle this in the final best model.
  - In general there is a lack of nonbinder data, make sure the models account for the severse class imbalance overall as well.
- Using the Held-out Test Set, per target performance varies dramatically, provide a correction to account for this in the model building. Any target that has a MCC = 1 likely has issues and should not be used as a target.
- Calibration failure: The ECE of 0.202 and MCE of 0.954 indicate that predicted probabilities do not reliably correspond to true binding rates. A predicted 70% binding probability does not mean 70% chance of binding — the model is overconfident in some probability bins and underconfident in others. This means probability thresholds should be interpreted with extreme caution, and conformal prediction sets should be preferred for decision-making.
  - What happens if a novel compound prediction using the trained model produces ambiguous conformal predictions?
- Include a predicted activity (greater or less than 10 micromolar).
- Make sure the types of models tested are RF, LightGBM, xgBoost, and GNN.

